revision.text:
"'''Nothing About Us Without Us!'''" ([[Latin]]: "'''Nihil de nobis, sine nobis'''") is a [[slogan]] used to communicate the idea that no policy should be decided by any representative without the full and direct participation of members the group(s) affected by that policy. This involves [[Nation state|national]], [[ethnic group|ethnic]], [[social model of disability|disability-based]], or other groups that are often thought to be marginalized from political, social, and economic opportunities.
The saying in its Latin form has its origins in [[Central European]] foreign relations, and is cited as a long standing principle of [[Hungary|Hungarian]] law and [[foreign policy]],<ref>{{Cite book| last = Bentley| first = R| title = Hungary, from 1848 to 1860| year = 1860| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=enuRlR0UHhoC&pg=PA173#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> and a cornerstone of the foreign policy of [[Second Polish Republic|interwar Poland]].<ref>{{Cite journal| volume = 16| issue = 48| pages = 558–571| last = Smogorzewski| first = Kazimierz| title = Poland's Foreign Relations| journal = The Slavonic and East European Review| year=1938|accessdate = 2010-06-22 | jstor = 4203420}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| pages = 47–88| editors = P Wandycz (ed.)| last = Kornat| first = Marek| coauthors = J Micgiel| title = Reflections on Polish Foreign Policy| chapter = The Policy of Equilibrium and Polish Bilateralism| year = 2007| url = http://politologia.wsb-nlu.edu.pl/uploadedFiles/file/M_Kornat%20-%20The%20Policy%20of%20Equilibrium%20and%20Polish%20Bilateralism.pdf|isbn=0-9654520-7-7}}</ref>
The term in its English form came into use in [[disability activism]] during the 1990s. [[James Charlton (activist)|James Charlton]] relates that he first heard the term used in talks by [[South African]] disability activists Michael Masutha and William Rowland, who had in turn heard the phrase used by an unnamed [[East European]] activist at an earlier international disability rights conference. In 1998, Charlton used the saying as title for a book on disability rights.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = University of California Press| isbn = 0-520-22481-7| last = Charlton| first = James I| title = Nothing About Us Without Us| accessdate = 2010-06-22| year = 1998| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=ohqff8DBt9gC&lpg=PA3&pg=PA3#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
The saying has since moved from the disability rights movement to other [[interest group]], [[identity politics]], and [[populism|populist]] movements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aidsalliance.org/publicationsdetails.aspx?id=310|title=Nothing about us without us: Greater, meaningful involvement of people who use illegal drugs|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sexworkawareness.org/nothing-about-us-without-us-the-shared-goals-of-the-harm-reduction-and-sex-worker-rights-movements|title=Nothing About Us Without Us: The Shared Goals of the Harm Reduction and Sex Worker Rights Movements|date=August 2, 2010}}</ref>
